questions.text: Do you want that PoxApp analyzes a photo of your skin lesion?
questions.details: PoxApp can analyze a photo of your skin lesion with methods of artificial intelligence. Your picture will be analyzed anonymously on your device and not sent to an external server.

Please take or select a close-up and well-lit picture of your skin lesion.

Do not photograph your head or body parts with a tattoo or birth mark.
Select one or more of the symptoms below. If you do not have any of the symptoms, click on "Next".

questions.text: On which date did the symptoms first appear?
Have you had close contact with a person confirmed to be infected with monkeypox?
questions.details:
Close contact with a confirmed case means:
  • Direct, physical contact (touching, shaking hands, kissing).
  • Contact with or exchange of body fluids.
  • Sharing an apartment.
  • Contact with bedding (including "making the bed").

questions.text: What was the date of the last contact?
Have you had intimate contact with people outside of a relationship in the past 21 days?

results.text:
The risk score for people with similar characteristics and behaviors is
Risk Score

Symptom Score
Exposition Score


What is the risk score and risk profile?

The PoxApp has calculated the risk profile for people with similar characteristics and behaviors. The risk profile consists of two risk dimensions, each of which can receive between 0 and 100 points. The risk score corresponds to the highest value of the two risk dimensions. A low score means that a related risk is considered to be rather low, while a high score may indicate a higher risk. The algorithms for the score calculations were developed by physicians of the PoxApp team, serve only as a rough orientation and are without guarantee.

These are the two risk dimensions:

1. Symptom Score: PoxApp has calculated this score for people with similar symptoms and a similar rash/skin lesion.

2. Exposition Score: This score was calculated for people with similar contacts and behaviors that promote transmission of the virus.

Few people with similar characteristics and behavior are infected with the monkeypox virus. %(result_ai)s Persons with new skin conditions are adviced to get in touch with a primary care physician or dermatologist.

%(v_orange)s Get in touch with a doctor.

Most people with similar characteristics and behavior are not infected with the monkeypox virus. If you develop further symptoms or a skin lesion, complete the survey of PoxApp again. Persons that fell ill or have symptoms are adviced to get in touch with a health care professional such as a primary care physician.
%(v_green)s Most people with similar characteristics and behavior are not infected with the monkeypox virus.

%(v_orange)s Post-exposure vaccination.

Many people with similar characteristics are eligible for vaccination. The CDC advises that individuals who have been exposed to the monkeypox virus be given the vaccine to prevent them from developing monkeypox. This is called post-exposure vaccination which is effective at preventing monkeypox when given within 4 days of exposure. If given between 4–14 days after the date of exposure, symptoms may be reduced, but infection may not be prevented from developing. For further clarification, please contact your local health department.
